# Building Journey Exercises

This document describes how to create exercises for new chapters. Each chapter builds on previous ones — techniques become longer, ranges expand, and new concepts layer on top of what the user already knows.

Always follow [language-and-messaging.mdc](language-and-messaging.mdc) for all user-facing text.

## File structure

Each chapter lives in its own file: `src/constants/journey/chapter{n}.ts`. Import the generator and modal builder at the top:

```typescript
import type { StageConfigInput } from "./types";
import { ExerciseGenerator, IntroModalGenerator } from "./exercise-😁generator";

const gen = new ExerciseGenerator();
const modal = new IntroModalGenerator();
```

Export two things:

- `CHAPTER_{N}_WARMUP: StageConfigInput` — warmup stage (chapter 1 has none)
- `CHAPTER_{N}_STAGES: StageConfigInput[]` — the main stages

Register them in `index.ts` as a `ChapterInput`.

## Chapter anatomy

### Warmup (chapter 2+)

Every chapter after chapter 1 starts with a warmup — prompted if >4h since last session. Warmups revisit familiar techniques at shorter durations. They should include:

- A breath exercise (sss-sss-zzz) — volume detection, ~15s
- A lip roll — tone-follow, ~4 plays
- A hum — hill sustain (~15s, increases in later chapters)
- Low Uu — hill sustain (~15s, increases in later chapters)
- Hoo hoo — zone above (~8s, increases in later chapters)
- Farinelli breathwork — ~5 cycles

### Stages

Group exercises into 4-6 stages per chapter. Each stage has a theme (e.g. "Wake Up", "First Sounds", "First Melody", "Breath"). The last exercise of the last stage carries the chapter's `completionModal`.

### Exercise order within a stage

1. Start gentle — hums, breath, or familiar territory
2. Introduce the new technique or concept mid-stage
3. Close with something grounding — breathwork, a sustain, or a return to a familiar sound

## Exercise types and generators

### Volume detection — `gen.volumeDetection()`

Mic detects any sound (no pitch). User makes sound for `targetSeconds`. Cues rotate on screen with per-cue timing.

```typescript
gen.volumeDetection({
  slug: "sss-zzz-sss",
  title: "Sss-zzz-sss",
  headerSubtitle: "Make sound · 18 seconds",
  cardSubtitle: "All breath, no voice — feel what happens",
  targetSeconds: 18,
  cues: [
    { text: "sss", seconds: 2 },
    { text: "zzz", seconds: 2 },
    { text: "sss", seconds: 2 },
  ],
  instruction:
    "Make a steady sss sound — no pitch needed, just breath.\nSwitch to zzz and feel the vibration start.\nIt's okay to take breaths between sounds.",
  introModal: modal.volumeDetection({
    targetSeconds: 18,
    instruction:
      "Make a steady sss sound — like air escaping. ...\n\nNotice how your body settles ...\n\nThis exercise wakes up your breath control ...\n\nKeep your mouth relaxed ...",
  }),
});
```

**Progression:** Used in early chapters for breath awareness (unpitched). In later chapters, pitched exercises (melody, sustain) largely replace volume detection — consonants like sss/zzz and vowels move into melody or sustain exercises where they follow specific pitches.

### Hill sustain — `gen.hillSustain()`

Ball rolls up/down a hill based on pitch direction. User sings in a zone (above, below, or between notes). The user decides how many tries they want — don't show rep counts like "5s × 3" in the `headerSubtitle` for hill exercises.

```typescript
gen.hillSustain({
  slug: "gentle-hum",
  note: 4, // chromatic degree from user's lowest note
  seconds: 5,
  direction: "down", // "up" | "down" | "between"
  title: "Gentle hum",
  headerSubtitle: "Hum · 5 seconds",
  cardSubtitle: "Your first pitched sound — a low, steady hum",
  instruction:
    "Hum mmmm on a low tone.\nFeel the buzz in your lips and chest.\nBreathe whenever you need to.",
  introModal: modal.hill({ seconds: 5, instruction: "..." }),
});
```

- `note: 4` = 4th chromatic degree from bottom (low register)
- `note: [5, 10]` with `direction: "between"` = range mode (sing between two notes)
- `direction: "down"` = ball rolls downhill (user sings below the note)
- `direction: "up"` = ball rolls uphill (user sings above the note)

**Low sounds should wobble:** For hill exercises targeting low notes (direction "down"), instruct the user to wobble/wave their voice slightly rather than holding a flat pitch. This keeps the voice loose and prevents tension. Add guidance like "Slightly wobble your voice" or "Let the sound wave gently" in the instruction.

**Progression:** Any chapter can use "down"/"up"/"between" directions. As chapters progress, "down" targets lower pitches and "up" targets higher pitches (expanding the user's range). "Between" exercises narrow the acceptable zone over time, building pitch precision.

### Zone above — `gen.zoneAbove()`

Like hill sustain but specifically for singing above a boundary note. Used for head voice exercises ("Hoo hoo"). This is not about holding a tone — it's about feeling head voice. Users are expected to "hoo hoo" many times in short bursts. Use shorter `seconds` than low-register hill exercises (e.g. 3–5s vs 5–8s for hums/Uu).

```typescript
gen.zoneAbove({
  slug: "hoo-hoo",
  boundaryNote: -6, // 6th from top
  seconds: 3,
  repeats: 3,
  title: "Hoo hoo",
  instruction:
    "Sing 'hoo hoo' on a high tone, like an owl.\nNotice the lightness.\nKeep it gentle.",
  introModal: modal.hill({ seconds: 3, reps: 3, instruction: "..." }),
});
```

### Sustain — `gen.sustain()`

Pitch-detection hold on a single note. User must match the pitch and hold it steady.

```typescript
gen.sustain({
  slug: "hum-mid-low",
  note: 4,
  seconds: 5,
  repeats: 3, // default 3
  title: "Hum — mid-low",
  headerSubtitle: "Hum · 5 seconds × 3",
  instruction:
    "Hum mmmm just above your lowest tone.\nNotice the warmth spreading through your chest.\nBreathe whenever you need to.",
  introModal: modal.sustain({ seconds: 5, instruction: "..." }),
});
```

**Progression:** Seconds increase (5 → 6 → 8 → 10). Notes move from low registers to mid and high. Later chapters add `toneShape` variations.

### Lip roll — `gen.lipRoll()`

Tone-follow: a reference tone plays and the user lip-rolls alongside it, sliding between two notes.

```typescript
gen.lipRoll({
  slug: "lip-roll-slide",
  startNote: -5,
  endNote: 4,
  requiredPlays: 3,
  scale: { type: "major", root: 1 }, // optional, default chromatic
  title: "Lip roll slide",
  headerSubtitle: "Glide high to low · play 3 times",
  instruction:
    "Lip roll alongside the tone.\nSlide smoothly from high to low — feel the glide.",
  introModal: modal.lipRoll({ requiredPlays: 3, instruction: "..." }),
});
```

**Progression:** Wider range (more notes between start and end). More required plays. Direction varies (high→low, low→high).

### Lip roll sustain — `gen.lipRollSustain()`

Tone-follow: hold the lip roll at a single steady pitch.

```typescript
gen.lipRollSustain({
  slug: "lip-roll-sustain",
  note: 5,
  seconds: 5,
  requiredPlays: 3,
  title: "Lip roll sustain",
  headerSubtitle: "Hold the buzz · play 3 times",
  instruction:
    "Lip roll alongside the tone.\nKeep the buzz steady.\nNotice where the resonance sits.",
  introModal: modal.lipRollSustain({ requiredPlays: 3, instruction: "..." }),
});
```

### Farinelli breathwork — `gen.farinelli()`

Breathing cycles (inhale-hold-exhale). No pitch detection. The component has built-in instruction — the exercise config does NOT need an `instruction` field.

```typescript
gen.farinelli({
  slug: "farinelli-1",
  maxCount: 7,
  title: "Farinelli breathwork",
  cardSubtitle: "Slow down. Breathe deep. Feel your body settle",
  introModal: modal.farinelli({
    title: "Farinelli breathwork",
    maxCount: 7,
    instruction:
      "Inhale, hold, and exhale for the same count — each cycle adds one beat.\n\nNotice how your body settles as the rhythm deepens.",
  }),
});
```

**Progression:** `maxCount` increases (5 → 7 → 9). Often placed at end of a stage as a grounding exercise.

### Melody — inline config

Melody exercises are typically written inline (not via generator) because each melody is unique. Use `IntroModalGenerator.melody()` for the intro modal.

```typescript
{
  exerciseTypeId: "melody",
  slug: "two-note-step",
  title: "Two-note step",
  headerSubtitle: "Sing two notes · listen and match",
  cardSubtitle: "Your first melody — just two adjacent notes",
  tempo: 50,
  melody: [
    {
      type: "chromatic",
      root: 1,
      events: [
        { type: "note", target: { kind: BandTargetKind.Index, i: 1 }, duration: 8 },
        { type: "note", target: { kind: BandTargetKind.Index, i: 3 }, duration: 8 },
        { type: "note", target: { kind: BandTargetKind.Index, i: 1 }, duration: 8 },
      ],
    },
  ],
  minScore: 0,
  instruction: "Sing the two notes as they appear.\nListen and match.\nThere's no rush.",
  introModal: modal.melody({ minScore: 0, instruction: "..." }),
}
```

Named melody generators are also available: `gen.majorSecond()`, `gen.fifth()`, `gen.octave()`, `gen.majorScale()`, `gen.minorScale()`, `gen.pentatonic()`, `gen.scaleDegrees()`.

**Progression:** More notes, wider intervals, faster tempos, higher `minScore` thresholds. Early chapters use `minScore: 0` (just follow along). Later chapters require 40–70%.

### Rhythm — inline config

Rhythm exercises use tap/pause patterns. Written inline.

```typescript
{
  exerciseTypeId: "rhythm",
  slug: "feel-the-beat",
  title: "Feel the Beat",
  cardSubtitle: "Tap along to the beat",
  tempo: 80,
  pattern: [
    { type: "pause", duration: NoteDuration.Quarter },  // intro beats
    { type: "tap", duration: NoteDuration.Quarter },
    { type: "tap", duration: NoteDuration.Quarter },
    { type: "pause", duration: NoteDuration.Half },
  ],
  metronome: true,
  minScore: 60,
  instruction: "Tap the spacebar or touch the screen on each beat",
  introModal: modal.rhythm({ minScore: 60, instruction: "..." }),
}
```

**Progression:** Faster tempos, more complex patterns (syncopation, dotted rhythms), higher `minScore`.

### Learn — inline config

Static content screens with text and video. No exercise mechanics.

```typescript
{
  exerciseTypeId: "learn",
  slug: "vocal-placement",
  title: "Vocal placement",
  cardSubtitle: "Notice where sound lives in your body — chest, throat, head",
  elements: [
    { type: "paragraph", text: "..." },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "...", variant: "secondary" },
    { type: "video" },
  ],
}
```

## Progression rules

### General

- **Vocal range expands**: early exercises stay near notes 1–7 (low register). Later chapters use the full range including negative indices (from top)
- **Durations increase**: sustain seconds grow from 5 → 6 → 8 → 10+
- **Accuracy thresholds rise**: `minScore` starts at 0, increases to 40, 60, 70+ in later chapters
- **New techniques layer on**: each chapter introduces at most 1–2 new exercise types or concepts

### Note numbering

Notes use 1-indexed chromatic degrees from the user's calibrated range:

- Positive: counted up from lowest note (1 = lowest, 4 = fourth from bottom)
- Negative: counted down from highest note (-1 = highest, -6 = sixth from top)
- This means the actual pitches adapt to each user's voice

### Vowels

Vowels progress from closed/warm to open/projecting:

1. **Uu** (as in "moon") — warmest, most grounding. Used first. Opens chest voice
2. **Oo** (as in "go") — slightly more open. Introduces rounded resonance
3. **Ah** (as in "father") — fully open. Stronger projection
4. **Ee** (as in "see") — forward, bright. Teaches projection and placement

Vowel modification exercises combine vowels in sequences:

- A-o-u-o-a — opening and closing
- ee-eh-ee — forward placement shifts
- ee-uu-ee — brightness to warmth contrast

### Intervals (melody exercises)

Progress from small to large:

1. Major second (2 semitones) — `gen.majorSecond()`, `chromaticDegree: 3`
2. Perfect fifth (7 semitones) — `gen.fifth()`, `chromaticDegree: 8`
3. Octave (12 semitones) — `gen.octave()`, `chromaticDegree: 13`

### Hill / balance exercises

Progress from loose to precise:

1. Direction-based: "sing anywhere below/above this note" (wide zone)
2. Range-based: "sing between these two notes" (narrowing zone)
3. Exact pitch: sustain exercises with tight tolerance

## Intro modal content

Every exercise (except learn) should have an `introModal`. Use `IntroModalGenerator` methods — they handle structure (video, headphones notice, subtitle patterns). You supply the `instruction` string containing the 4-section text.

The 4-section pattern (**do → feel → reason → reassurance**) is separated by `\n\n`:

```typescript
introModal: modal.sustain({
  seconds: 5,
  instruction:
    "Hum mmmm just above your lowest comfortable tone. Keep it steady and warm.\n\n" +
    "Notice the warmth spreading through your chest. Feel where the buzz sits.\n\n" +
    "Humming at this pitch grounds your voice in your body. It's a return to the simplest sound — a foundation before melody.\n\n" +
    "Breathe whenever you need to.",
});
```

Farinelli is a special case — it requires `title` because it has custom element layout (warning, tips, video):

```typescript
introModal: modal.farinelli({
  title: "Farinelli breathwork",
  maxCount: 7,
  instruction:
    "Inhale, hold, and exhale for the same count...\n\nNotice how your body settles...",
});
```

## `cardSubtitle` usage

Not every exercise needs a `cardSubtitle`. Use it:

- Early in a chapter when introducing new techniques
- For the first exercise of a new type
- When the sensation is worth describing

Omit it for later exercises in a chapter and in more advanced chapters — the `headerSubtitle` format hint is enough once the user has the feel of the practice.

## `minScore: 0` — special display case

When `minScore` is 0, the exercise is exploratory — no scoring pressure. The intro modal subtitle reflects this:

- `minScore > 0`: "Sing along — match 60% to continue"
- `minScore: 0`: "Sing along — just follow the notes"

## Completion modal

Only the last exercise of the last stage in a chapter gets a `completionModal`. Follow the pattern from language-and-messaging.mdc:

- Title: "Chapter {n} Complete"
- Subtitle: chapter name
- First paragraph: feeling first, accomplishment second
- Second paragraph (secondary): tease next chapter
- `confetti: true`
